                  <headline>Denmark lends Ireland 3 billion DKR</headline>
                  <intro><![CDATA[Today Ireland is expected to receive the first tranche of ¾ billion DKR from a Danish loan of 3 billion DKR in total. The loan is the Danish contribution to getting Ireland’s economy back on track. ”I am satisfied that Denmark is supporting Ireland in that process,” says minister for economic affairs and the interior Ms. Margrethe Vestager.]]></intro>
                  <body><![CDATA[
<p>Ireland is working for a recovery of its economy and the work is
steadily progressing. That is clear from the latest review of
Ireland's international financial assistance programme by the IMF,
the Commission and the ECB. Ireland achieved overall positive
growth in 2011, which is expected to continue in 2012. At the same
time, the market interest rates for Irish sovereign bonds are
declining from the very high levels at the peak of the
crisis.&nbsp;Now the Irish have even more grounds for optimism.</p>

<p>Today, the first of four tranches of ¾ billion DKR from Denmark
will be disbursed. In total, Denmark has offered to lend Ireland 3
billion DKR as part of the combined international financial
assistance programme that was requested by Ireland in late 2010.
The loan is provided subject to the condition that the Irish
government continues the work on getting the public finances under
control and "cleaning up" the banking sector, which helped cause
the crisis in Ireland.</p>

<p>Minister for economic affairs and the interior Ms. Margrethe
Vestager says:<br />
 "Ireland is on track with recovering its economy after its serious
financial and economic crisis. Ireland demonstrates that it is
possible to pull free from the crisis. But it takes political will
to implement reforms and create a better balance between public
revenues and expenditures, as Ireland has had to do. It is
important that Denmark contributes and I am satisfied we can
support Ireland in that process. On the one hand we must require
from ourselves and every individual country that we take
responsibility for creating sustainability and credibility of
economic policies. But at the same time we should show solidarity
with those who are taking responsibility and who have gotten into
serious economic problems."</p>

<p>Ireland's fiscal deficit is expected to be 10 percent of GDP in
2011 - the target is 10.6 percent at most. For 2012, the target is
8.6 percent of GDP which Ireland is also expected to achieve. In
2015 at the latest, Ireland's fiscal deficit must be below 3
percent of GDP.</p>

<p><strong>Facts about the financial assistance programme for
Ireland:</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>The international financial assistance programme for Ireland of
67.5 billion euro was agreed in late&nbsp;2010.&nbsp;</li>

<li>The Danish loan is 3 billion DKR in total and is disbursed in
four tranches in the period 2012-2013.</li>

<li>Besides Denmark, other contributors are the EU, the euro area
member states, the IMF, the UK and&nbsp;Sweden.&nbsp;</li>

<li>The financial assistance programme runs until late 2013 and is
reviewed quarterly by lenders to&nbsp;ensure that the successive
disbursements are made under the condition that Ireland
continues&nbsp;work on the recovery of its economy and returns to a
healthy and sustainable track.</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>

<p>Special Advisor Mr. Thomas W. Andersen, tel. +45 72 28 26 11</p>
